english:
  title: Preface to a Poem Sent as Farewell Gift to Pan, an Envoy Returning Home
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have long pondered the words of the Commentary on the Book of Changes, which tells us: "The Yellow Emperor, Yao, and Shun let their robes hang naturally, and the world was well ordered—for they took inspiration from Heaven and Earth." The ancients said this meant the upper and lower garments symbolized heaven and earth. Yet I venture to suggest that it is not merely robes that possess this upper and lower distinction. The ranks of official vestments, their grades high and low, stand firm and immovable—like heaven and earth themselves. When superiors and inferiors each maintain their proper stations in harmony and without coveting more, does not the world achieve order?

    In ancient times, the sages observed the patterns of heaven and earth and established vestments accordingly. From the nine-embroidered robe down to the single-embroidered robe, they created five grades of dress. In parallel, they divided lands among nobles in five ranks. Observing the magnitude of each person's virtue, they assigned stations high and low, distributing the five grades of vestments to match the five ranks of office. Position and virtue aligned; dress and person suited each other. Could this spring from mere artifice and self-interest? No—it was only to serve and honor Heaven itself. Thus it is said: "Heaven bestows its mandate upon those of virtue through the five vestments and five embroideries." In the time of the Yellow Emperor, Yao, and Shun, rank and distinction were already established, superior and inferior lived in harmony, much as Heaven distributes to all creatures their proper scale—the vast and minute, high and low each finding its rightful place—and thus the world was greatly well-ordered.

    With reverence, I consider that the Imperial Court, possessing the virtue of the Yellow Emperor, Yao, and Shun, has established harmonious and peaceful rule. Its ministers of state are like Gao, Kui, Ji, and Xie of old, cooperating in moral transformation and illuminating imperial wisdom. Deep benevolence and generous grace blanket all beneath Heaven. Our sovereign, in faithful service above and compassionate governance below, compares well to the ancient princes. The Emperor, approving greatly, has specially granted vestments of nine embroiderings and rank equal to a prince—bestowing honor in signal fashion. Thus the court selected from its worthy officials one versed in letters and righteous conduct, upright in bearing and gentle in speech, one capable of spreading imperial grace and winning hearts. The Lord Pan Jingzhao of the Bureau of Receptions has been chosen and dispatched here.

    Our sovereign and people receive this with utmost reverence and gratitude, vowing that generations hence shall not forsake this mandate. Thereupon the literary scholars of our realm spoke together, saying: "The nine-embroidered vestment is what the Son of Heaven grants to relatives of state and honored princes, bestowing the nine orders of rank and treating them as first among public officials. Even for those holding the rank of marquis or earl in the Middle Kingdom, such bestowal is difficult to obtain. Yet now our sovereign receives this mandate directly! The sacred precedent of antiquity, whereby Heaven commanded virtue, is revived in our present age. The exceptional honor the great court bestows upon imperial relations now extends to our humble realm—a fortune encountered scarcely once in a thousand years. And I myself witness it this day! How blessed we are!" With joy overwhelming, verses burst forth like songs, and though crude and ungainly in their expression, they would be presented as farewell gifts to the Lord Pan as he returns home. I am asked to compose this preface.

    I hold that the system of official vestments, establishing rank from high to low, is like heaven and earth—immutable indeed. Yet the hexagram of Peace shows Heaven below and Earth above, the two forces intermingling to achieve generative power. Therefore, though the distinction between superior and inferior remains firm, their sentiments must remain connected. To establish the hierarchy is to ground its proper form; to maintain connection is to enable its proper function. When form is grounded, propriety arises—order reigns without chaos. When function flows, music emerges—contentment abounds as people cherish one another. This is how the sage aligns heaven and earth within this world, using propriety and music to refine all people, extending from the intimate to the distant with impartial benevolence, thereby uniting the aspirations and fulfilling the responsibilities of all under Heaven.

    Now the Emperor, granting official vestments and elevating our sovereign's rank to that of imperial kinship, fulfills both visions—the fixed positions of heaven and earth, and their dynamic intercourse. Thus he restores world order and revives the effortless governance of Yao and Shun, while uplifting all four seas through their encompassing benevolence. Propriety and music flourish abundantly, filling and overflowing. Sublime indeed! One born into this age may find happiness in honest toil as a common subject. How much more so for one of scholarly refinement who enters official service, receives imperial commission, and spreads the sovereign's word—bearing crowns across ten thousand leagues and immortalizing names in the histories! Surely Lord Pan achieves great honor. Upon his return, may he devote himself ever more to assisting the imperial endeavor, adorning all with refined culture and illuminating propriety and music with literary brilliance. Thus shall all within the realm, far and wide, share in the blessings of peaceful prosperity—this is Lord Pan's own aspiration and the earnest hope of our people.
  footnotes:
    - The Yellow Emperor, Yao, and Shun are legendary sage-kings of ancient China, revered in Confucian tradition as models of virtuous rule.
    - The 'nine embroideries' (九章) refer to the highest grade of official robes, symbolizing supreme authority and virtue.
    - The reference to Gao, Kui, Ji, and Xie alludes to legendary ministers of antiquity known for their wisdom and service.
    - The hexagram of Peace (泰) represents the harmonious interaction of heaven and earth, a key concept in Change philosophy.
    - This preface celebrates both the honor bestowed upon the Korean sovereign and the role of the envoy Pan Jingzhao in conveying imperial grace.
